\subsection{Colorblind-Friendly Themes}{

The following themes encode bull/bear direction in ways that remain
distinguishable under the most common color-vision deficiencies. The
colorways for \code{bloomberg_terminal}, \code{limit_up}, and \code{bid_n_ask} are
derived from the Okabe & Ito (2008) qualitative palette, the de-facto
standard for accessible scientific visualization.

\describe{
\item{\code{limit_up}, \code{hawks_and_doves}, \code{trust_the_process}}{Encode
direction with luminance only. Safe under deuteranopia, protanopia,
tritanopia, and full achromatopsia.}
\item{\code{bloomberg_terminal}}{Orange + neutral gray. Safe under all
three CVD types thanks to Okabe-Ito-style hue separation.}
\item{\code{default}, \code{payout}}{Cyan/teal + blue or dark slate. Safe under
all three CVD types — the color pair sits inside the blue-yellow
axis that CVD users perceive normally.}
\item{\code{bid_n_ask}}{Blue + red. Safe under deuteranopia and
protanopia (the most common forms, affecting ~8\% of males); the
pair separates more weakly under tritanopia.}
}

\code{tp_slapped} is the only built-in that uses a teal/red pair adjacent to
the red-green CVD axis; prefer the themes above when accessibility
matters.
}

\subsection{Theme Properties}{

Each theme sets the following color properties:

\describe{
\item{Candle colors}{\code{bearish_body}, \code{bearish_wick}, \code{bearish_border},
\code{bullish_body}, \code{bullish_wick}, \code{bullish_border}}
\item{General colors}{\code{background_color}, \code{foreground_color} (axes and
borders), \code{text_color}}
\item{Grid and reference}{\code{gridcolor}, \code{threshold_color} (horizontal
reference lines such as overbought/oversold levels)}
\item{Colorway}{A vector of 10 colors cycled through for indicator
lines and legends}
}

Any of these properties can be individually overridden via the \code{...}
argument to \code{\link[=set_theme]{set_theme()}}.
}
}
\examples{
## list available themes
talib::set_theme()

## apply a theme by name
talib::set_theme("payout")

## apply a theme with custom overrides
talib::set_theme(
  "hawks_and_doves",
  background_color = "#FAFAFA"
)

## override individual properties
## without switching theme
talib::set_theme(
  bearish_body = "#FF4444",
  bullish_body = "#44FF44"
)

## reset to default theme
talib::set_theme("default")
}
